The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Sharfuddin Ansari, 24, died after being knocked down by an autorickshaw near Girachand Lane, in the Beniapukur police station area, on Monday evening. Police said Ansari was crossing the road when the mishap occurred. Local residents took him to National Medical College and Hospital, where he was declared dead. The driver managed to flee.

 Kuntal Singha Roy, a traffic sergeant, was hit by a motorcycle on Monday morning at the crossing of Hazra and Richie Road. Police said Dhirendra Pandey, the motorcyclist, knocked down Roy while trying to swerve past a bus. Both Roy and Pandey were taken to a private hospital, from where they were released after treatment.

 traffic constable was injured when a school bus hit him at the AJC Bose Road-SN Banerjee Road crossing. Police said the constable, Paresh Roy, was injured in the chest and taken to NRS Hospital. He was later shifted to Calcutta Police Hospital. The driver has been arrested.

 A 48-year-old woman, wife of an army officer, tried to commit suicide by jumping into the Hooghly on Monday morning. Police said the woman left her Fort William residence and headed for a ghat near Babughat from where she jumped into the water. Some fishermen came to her rescue and handed her over to police. The woman was admitted to Command Hospital.

 Two burglars were arrested on Monday in Narkeldanga and Joynagar on charges of stealing two cellphones and gold ornaments, worth Rs 55,000, from a house on Karl Marx Sarani. Police said the stolen items were recovered from the two, identified as Kader Sheikh and Shamsher. A search is on for the other gang members.

 Of the 75 Left Front councillors, only 21 turned up at the civic reception of Nguyen Thi Binh, the former vice-president of Vietnam, on Monday. Among the absentees was mayoral council member (solid waste management) Chandana Ghosh Dastidar. 

 ivic employees were asked to fill up the vacant seats in the council chamber. It is a shame. I am surprised at the scant presence of the Left Front councillors, said mayor Bikash Ranjan Bhattacharyya. According to the mayors office, all the councillors were sent invitations by Saturday but none confirmed participation. 

 Arun Kumar Lahiri, mathematician and Sanskrit scholar, died last Saturday at the age of 77. He was the editor of the Bisuddhasiddhanta Panjika. Earlier, Lahiri had been selected a member of the Calendar Reforms Committee under Meghnad Saha in 1952. This led to the creation of the Indian Ephemeris and Nautical Almanac. He was also instrumental in establishing the Positional Astronomy Centre. He left behind his wife and daughter.

